{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631266","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631266"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:25:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17359"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17359"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70121"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10049"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17359"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5390"},{"type":"tags","id":"7820"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23536"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70121"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA diagnostic test for a medical condition has the following characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESensitivity: 95%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpecificity: 85%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDisease prevalence in the population: 1%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best represents the positive predictive value of this test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["6%","25%","85%","50%","95%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBayes\u0027 theorem is a mathematical formula that describes how to update the probability of a hypothesis when given new evidence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUsing Bayes\u0027 theorem, we can calculate that the \u003Cstrong\u003Epositive predictive value is 6%\u003C/strong\u003E. This means that only 6% of positive test results are true positives, despite the test having high sensitivity and specificity. This surprisingly low value is due to the low disease prevalence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe calculation using Bayes\u0027 theorem is:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrior probability (prevalence) = 0.01\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELikelihood ratio = (Sensitivity)/(1-Specificity) = 0.95/0.15 = 6.33\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPosterior probability = (0.01 \u00d7 6.33)/(0.01 \u00d7 6.33 + 0.99 \u00d7 0.15) = 0.06 or 6%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are incorrect:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E25%\u003C/strong\u003E is an arbitrary value not related to the test characteristics\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E85%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the test\u0027s specificity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E95%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the test\u0027s sensitivity\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E50%\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest random chance, which does not apply here\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis demonstrates how disease prevalence significantly affects a test\u0027s predictive value, even when the test has good sensitivity and specificity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bayes\u0027 theorem calculates the probability of a hypothesis being true given new evidence by incorporating prior probability and likelihood ratios.","The positive predictive value of a test increases with higher disease prevalence in the population being tested.","Pre-test probability significantly influences the interpretation of diagnostic test results."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17359"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-13T19:35:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-13T19:40:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10049"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70121"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organiz